Jerry is too far north to gain any strength, Karen is disorganised and will only get weaker at landfall... no hurricanes from those 2 (definitely not major status), but Lorenzo is very well organised and gaining strength rapidly over warm waters and has a long westerly run to strengthen, how much it strengthens is a question of how fast it travels across the Atlantic (slower = increasingly likely to gain strength) and trajectory (too far north and it hits cooler waters and will likely peak at cat 3 before travelling back East and dissipating), the more westerly the trajectory the more likely a cat 4... the NHC is predicting major hurricane status (cat 3) around Friday, It should be listed as a cat 1 by the next NHC update (max sustained winds of 74mph recorded). Waters in the Atlantic are beginning to cool so Hurricane season is beyond the half way line, but it's interesting that more activity is picking up...

Earth's rotation, high humidity, temperatures in the ocean cause confusion in the atmosphere. Out of 60 of these formations, 10% by gathered energy from the Atlantic Ocean to becomes a hurricane. Scientists are closely following these upheavals and trying to determine which ones may be potentially dangerous 1-2 weeks in advance. To reduce the likelihood of undesirable events, even reverse the process, for accurate predictions with these, it may also benefit from a mix of old and new ancient knowledge. Knowing that weather forecasts 5 days, much less 1 year in advance are tentative at best, I didn't give "2" a 100% probability. escalating patterns of extreme weather historically combined with increased rainfall (~11%) in the gulf and above average temperatures (https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/sotc/national/?Set-Language=ar) make the high end of avg more likely. need to look into how rainfall and temperature correspond to hurricanes historically, but it seems like a reasonable place to start. avg per wikipedia seems to be 1-3 cat 4s and 0-1 cat 5s in the last 20 years, but cat 5s are sporadic. if we assume 2 cat 4s and 1 cat 5 this would seem reasonably within a standard deviation from the escalating moving average. 4 or more is more rare, but is also the only answer with an infinite number of possible outcomes included, so I increased it. My starting point was 0-1%, 1-4%, 2-10%, 3-45%, 4 or more - 40%. After considering the other possible but more rare outcomes (5, 6, 7 etc) which would account probably for 1-5% in decreasing likelihood (4% for 5, 3% for 6, etc), I increased my 4 or more number by the sum of the %s for 5-8 (10%) and subtracted the amounts in descending order from the other 4 options (though left 0 at 1% pending the first cat 4 storm of the season). From the NOAA and Wikipedia websites, it seems that there were 65 cat 4 or 5 Hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean in the period 1979 - 2008 (40 Seasons). This is an average of 1.625 such hurricanes per year. Some years there were no major hurricanes (83, 86, 87, 90, 93, 94, 97, 06, 12, 13) whilst in others there were 4 or more (99, 04, 05, 10, 17), or 3 (88, 95, 08) . From this it would appear that the greatest probability would be 1 or 2 hurricanes. Looking in more detail, hurricanes seem to be dependent upon (i) the ocean surface temperature (if it is over approx 26.5 degrees Celsius then hurricanes can more easily form and there is a correlation between increased surface temp and increased storm intensity) and (ii) the shearing winds over the ocean which will hinder hurricane formation if they are strong. The shearing winds appear to be related to the El Nino effect, such that in significant El Nino years there are increased shearing winds over the Atlantic and fewer hurricanes develop. Over the last 40 years, El Nino effects were significant in 80, 83, 86, 87, 91, 93, 94, 97, 02, 04, 06, 09, 14, 15 and 19. They apparently are cyclical, with effects lasting for around 6-18 months and occurring every 2-5 years on average. There is a very noticeable correlation between the El Nino years and the years in which there were none or only one major hurricane (cat 4 or above). This would seem to suggest that in an El Nino year, there is more chance of none or only one major hurricane.
~6 year cycle likely peaked in 2017, putting us in Year 2 of a ~3 year drop (usually to 0 major storms). Most probable we land within 1 of last year.
